Step-by-Step Guide for Jenkins Pipeline Setup
Project Structure Understanding:

You have a unittests directory containing the test files (e.g., test_action.py, test_application.py, etc.).
You also have a utils directory containing the main code files (e.g., action.py, add_application.py, etc.).
The test files seem to follow the standard naming convention for unittest or pytest.
Creating a Jenkinsfile: You’ll need to create a Jenkinsfile in the root of your repository. This file will tell Jenkins how to set up the environment, install dependencies, and run your tests.

Jenkinsfile Content: Use the following template for your Jenkinsfile. This script is customized to your setup and uses pytest to run the tests.

pipeline {
    agent { label 'rhel8' } // Ensure this label matches your Jenkins node's label
    environment {
        PYTHON_ENV = '/usr/bin/python3.11' // Path to Python 3.11 executable
        VENV_DIR = 'venv' // Directory for virtual environment
    }
    stages {
        stage('Prepare Environment') {
            steps {
                sh '''
                    # Check if Python 3.11 is available
                    ${PYTHON_ENV} --version
                    
                    # Create a virtual environment
                    ${PYTHON_ENV} -m venv ${VENV_DIR}
                    
                    # Activate virtual environment
                    source ${VENV_DIR}/bin/activate
                    
                    # Upgrade pip to the latest version
                    pip install --upgrade pip
                '''
            }
        }
        stage('Install Dependencies') {
            steps {
                sh '''
                    # Activate virtual environment
                    source ${VENV_DIR}/bin/activate
                    
                    # Install dependencies from requirements.txt
                    if [ -f requirements.txt ]; then
                        pip install -r requirements.txt
                    fi
                '''
            }
        }
        stage('Run Unit Tests') {
            steps {
                sh '''
                    # Activate virtual environment
                    source ${VENV_DIR}/bin/activate
                    
                    # Run all tests in the unittests folder
                    pytest unittests/ --junitxml=report.xml
                '''
            }
        }
    }
    post {
        always {
            // Archive test results to Jenkins
            junit 'report.xml'
        }
    }
}



Step-by-Step Explanation:

agent { label 'rhel8' }: Specifies the Jenkins node to run this pipeline. Ensure this label matches the node where Python 3.11 is installed.
Environment Variables:
PYTHON_ENV: Path to Python 3.11 on your system.
VENV_DIR: Directory name for the virtual environment.
Stages:
Prepare Environment:
Checks Python 3.11 version.
Creates a virtual environment in the specified directory.
Upgrades pip to the latest version.
Install Dependencies:
Installs dependencies from requirements.txt (if present).
Run Unit Tests:
Runs all test files in the unittests/ directory using pytest.
Generates a report in report.xml format for Jenkins to parse.
Post Actions:
Archives the test results (report.xml) in Jenkins for review.
Adding Jenkinsfile to Your Repository:

Save the Jenkinsfile in the root of your repository.
Commit and push it to your version control system.
Create and Configure Jenkins Job:

In Jenkins, create a new pipeline job.
Link the job to your repository (where the Jenkinsfile is located).
Ensure the Jenkins node labeled rhel8 is available and has Python 3.11 installed.
Run the Jenkins Job:

Click Build Now to run the job.
Monitor the console output for any errors.
Review Test Results:

After the build completes, you should see the test results in the Test Results section of the Jenkins job.
Troubleshooting Tips:
Virtual Environment Issues:

Make sure the virtual environment is created successfully by checking the console output.
If the virtual environment is not activating properly, check the path of PYTHON_ENV.
Dependency Installation:

Ensure that your requirements.txt file is present and correctly formatted.
If there are issues with installing dependencies, they will be shown in the console output.
Test Execution:

If no tests are being discovered, make sure the pytest command is pointing to the correct directory (unittests/).
Test Reporting:

Make sure that the report.xml is being generated. If not, there might be an issue with the test execution.

